    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.24.6a"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">66-1 Neihardt Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">6a</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="italics"><hi rend="caps">C.M.</hi> Blasingame
                        <lb/>
                    Star Route
                        <lb/>
                    Avenal, California</hi>
                        <lb/>
                    "<hi rend="italics">Luck of Lost Canyon</hi>"
                        <lb/>
                    "<hi rend="italics">Longhorns of</hi> 1880"
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>May 27, 1956.</dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt, Sr.,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Rt 6,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Missouri.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I have just read <hi rend="caps">WHEN THE TREE FLOWERED</hi>--a wonderful book. I was raised in the west-of-the-Missouri region of South Dakota. It was almost like being ba<del>v</del><add>c</add>k home again, as I turned page after page and came across word after word of the Sioux language which I recognized. Actually there are four dialects but the Oglala<sic>Ogallala</sic> words are most familiar to me. The Teton changed most of his d's to l's--Dakota to Lakota, for example-- but anyway, I was delighted to be able to understand their meaning.. Another nice thing I noticed, that <del>i</del><add>y</add>ou did not attempt t<del>p</del><add>o</add> spell the Indian word correctly, in quite a number of instances, but <hi rend="underline">wrote it as it sounds</hi>, which makes it so much easier for those who couldn't possibly recognize the word any other way. I much appreciated this.</p>
                
                <p>Another thing-- You have let your characters tell their story in the slow, repetitious and "round-about-way" which is the true Indian way of telling their legends and stories. It is good to read a book which sticks so closely to actuality.</p>
                
                <p>I wish to know whether there are any copies of this bo<del>k</del><add>o</add>k available now? Is it possible to have an autographed copy?</p>
                
                <p>I would appreciate <del><unclear>a</unclear></del><add>h</add>earing from you on this, and I would be very happy to buy an autographed book, if possible.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>With kindest regards to you, </salute>
                
                    <salute>Sincerely yours,</salute>
                    <signed>C.M. Blasingame.</signed>
                    <signed>C.M. Blasingame.</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <note type="recipient">ansd 6-15-56</note>           
       
            </div1>
        </body>
        
